  {
      "id": "allergy-hayfever",
      "name": "Allergy & Hay-Fever",
      "category": "Chest & Breathing",
      "tags": [
          "allergies",
          "hay fever",
          "histamine",
          "mast cells",
          "wei qi",
          "hypervigilance"
      ],
      "riskLevel": "Medical monitoring recommended",
      "emotionalRoot": "Hypervigilance, weak energetic boundaries, early unsafety, and a body that may treat neutral contact with the world as threat.",
      "metaphor": "Your immune system is a retired, paranoid mall cop at a garden center, macing rose bushes because pollen had the audacity to exist.",
      "physiologicalDescription": "Allergies and hay fever involve IgE-mediated immune recognition, mast cell degranulation, histamine release, mucus production, itching, swelling, sneezing, and nervous-system amplification.",
      "sarcasticAdvice": "You may not be allergic to the world. You may be running an ancient threat-detection program that now treats pollen like it kicked in your door.",
      "physicalTherapyTip": "For mild symptoms only, sit upright, breathe in through the nose for 4 seconds, exhale for 8 seconds, and use warmth over the upper chest while repeating a safety cue. Use allergy medication and medical care as directed.",
      "mindfulnessPrompts": [
          "Where does my body still believe the world is unsafe?",
          "What neutral situation do I keep treating like danger?",
          "Who or what taught my system to stay on alert?",
          "What would it feel like to let my boundary be strong without being hostile?"
      ],
      "structuredContent": {
          "version": 1,
          "hero": {
              "primaryPattern": "Mast cell sensitization, histamine release, Wei Qi boundary weakness, and nervous-system hypervigilance may amplify allergic reactivity.",
              "cascade": [
                  "Environmental Contact",
                  "Wei Qi Boundary Alarm",
                  "Mast Cell Priming",
                  "Histamine Storm",
                  "Mucus & Itch Response",
                  "Hypervigilance Feedback Loop"
              ],
              "tags": [
                  "#wei qi shield",
                  "#mast cell calm",
                  "#ghost alarm"
              ],
              "safetyPreview": "Severe swelling, throat tightness, wheezing, trouble breathing, fainting, blue lips, or signs of anaphylaxis require emergency care."
          },
          "biologyPathway": [
              {
                  "title": "Environmental Contact",
                  "short": "Pollen, dust, mold, or dander contacts a sensitized system.",
                  "detail": "Allergy symptoms often begin when pollen, dust mites, mold spores, animal dander, or other triggers contact the nose, eyes, throat, airway, or skin. The trigger may be harmless by itself, but the immune system has learned to treat it as a threat."
              },
              {
                  "title": "IgE Recognition",
                  "short": "The immune system flags the trigger.",
                  "detail": "In allergic patterns, IgE antibodies can bind to allergens and cross-link receptors on mast cells and basophils. That immune recognition tells the body to launch a defensive response even when the substance is not truly dangerous."
              },
              {
                  "title": "Mast Cell Degranulation",
                  "short": "Mast cells dump inflammatory chemicals.",
                  "detail": "Mast cells release histamine, leukotrienes, prostaglandins, cytokines, and other inflammatory mediators. This is the chemical alarm bell behind itching, sneezing, watery eyes, swelling, mucus, and airway irritation."
              },
              {
                  "title": "Histamine Storm",
                  "short": "Vessels leak, tissues swell, mucus rises.",
                  "detail": "Histamine increases blood-vessel permeability and irritates nerve endings. The result can be runny nose, congestion, watery eyes, itching, flushing, sneezing, throat irritation, and a body that acts like spring is an invading army."
              },
              {
                  "title": "Nervous-System Amplification",
                  "short": "Stress lowers the reaction threshold.",
                  "detail": "Stress chemistry, sympathetic activation, and low vagal tone can make immune reactions feel louder and harder to settle. The body may become quicker to flare, slower to calm, and more likely to treat neutral contact as danger."
              },
              {
                  "title": "Safety Escalation Check",
                  "short": "Know when allergy becomes emergency.",
                  "detail": "Mild hay fever is one thing. Trouble breathing, throat tightness, tongue or lip swelling, fainting, confusion, blue lips, or a rapidly spreading whole-body reaction is not a journaling prompt. That is emergency territory."
              }
          ],
          "interpretations": {
              "clinical": {
                  "label": "Strictly Medical",
                  "title": "Mast Cell & Histamine Cascade",
                  "sections": [
                      {
                          "heading": "Stage 1 — Sensitized Immune Recognition",
                          "body": [
                              "Allergies and hay fever involve an immune system that has learned to identify a normally harmless substance as a threat.",
                              "Common triggers include pollen, dust mites, mold, pet dander, grasses, weeds, trees, smoke, perfumes, and environmental irritants. The trigger is not necessarily dangerous. The immune interpretation is the problem."
                          ]
                      },
                      {
                          "heading": "Stage 2 — IgE and Mast Cell Activation",
                          "body": [
                              "IgE antibodies can bind to allergens and cross-link receptors on mast cells. Once the mast cell receives enough signal, it degranulates.",
                              "Degranulation releases histamine and other inflammatory mediators. This is the biochemical alarm behind sneezing, itching, watery eyes, swelling, congestion, and mucus."
                          ]
                      },
                      {
                          "heading": "Stage 3 — Histamine Storm",
                          "body": [
                              "Histamine increases blood-vessel permeability, irritates sensory nerves, and increases mucus production.",
                              "The nose runs, the eyes water, the throat scratches, the skin itches, and the airway may feel irritated or tight. The body is trying to flush out an invader, even when the invader is just pollen existing like a botanical idiot."
                          ]
                      },
                      {
                          "heading": "Stage 4 — Stress and Vagal Tone",
                          "body": [
                              "Stress does not mean allergies are imaginary. It means the nervous system and immune system talk to each other.",
                              "Low vagal tone, chronic sympathetic arousal, poor sleep, and ongoing hypervigilance can lower the threshold for immune reactivity. The allergy pathway becomes easier to trigger and harder to calm."
                          ]
                      }
                  ]
              },
              "witty": {
                  "label": "Comedic & Witty",
                  "title": "The Retired Mall Cop at the Garden Center",
                  "paragraphs": [
                      "Your immune system is now a retired, paranoid mall cop who was fired from the mall and now works as a greeter at a garden center. He has a whistle around his neck, a flashlight with dead batteries, and a binder full of suspicious persons that includes every living plant, animal, and dust mote in a three-mile radius.",
                      "Your mast cells are his trigger finger. Every time a pollen grain floats past, not attacking, just existing, just doing its botanical job of making baby plants, the mall cop screams CONTACT and hits the alarm.",
                      "Histamine floods the scene. Your nose becomes a faucet. Your eyes swell. Your throat tightens like someone filed paperwork to temporarily close the airway.",
                      "But here is the absurd part: there is no intruder. It is pollen. It has no agenda. It does not know you exist. It just wants to find another flower.",
                      "Your mast cells are not fighting an enemy. They are fighting the memory of an enemy. Somewhere in your life, your nervous system installed a security system that never got the memo that the war ended.",
                      "Now you sneeze at sunshine. You itch at air. The mall cop is standing in the gardening aisle macing a rose bush, and you are paying for the cleanup.",
                      "The garden center has a break room with a coffee mug that says WORLD'S OKAYEST DEFENDER. The microwave has been beeping for three years. No one has turned it off.",
                      "The mall cop has a schedule he wrote himself: ALERT, ALL SHIFT, EVERY SHIFT. His binder has tabs labeled POLLEN, DUST, MOLD, and UNTITLED, PROBABLY ALSO DANGEROUS. The untitled tab has four hundred pages.",
                      "The worst part? The mall cop reports directly to you. You sign his paychecks. You wrote the schedule. You gave him the binder. Every time you brace for the worst, every time you assume the other shoe will drop, every time you scan the room for threats, you train the mall cop. And the mall cop is just following orders."
