    "category": "Chest & Breathing",
    "emotionalRoot": "Long-standing, unresolved emotional problems, holding on to anger or hostility, constant vigilance, and hyper-reactivity to environmental threats.",
    "metaphor": "Your cardiovascular plumbing pressurized to maximum capacity because your mind thinks the world is a constant combat zone requiring immediate explosive reflexes.",
    "physiologicalDescription": "Chronic sympathetic nervous system activation drives vasoconstriction, elevates cardiac output, and stimulates the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system (RAAS), leading to persistent arterial wall tension.",
    "sarcasticAdvice": "Incredible. Continue holding onto that deep, simmered rage while you drink your salted caramel lattes. I'm sure your blood vessels enjoy being pressurized like a fire hose just because someone took your parking spot.",
    "mindfulnessPrompts": [
      "What deep, unspoken anger or resentment am I storing inside my heart instead of letting it pass?",
      "Am I ready to accept that the world does not need me to be on high-alert constant defense to survive?"
    ],
    "physicalTherapyTip": "Practice the 4-7-8 breathing technique (inhale for 4s, hold for 7s, exhale for 8s through pursed lips) for 5 minutes. This can support parasympathetic activation and help manage symptom sensitivity.",
